## Severity Definitions

- critical: Exploitable security vulnerability, data loss risk, or production-breaking defect. Blocks merge.
- high: Significant bug, serious security weakness, or substantial quality regression. Blocks merge.
- medium: Non-blocking issue with meaningful impact — logic flaw, missing test coverage, notable style violation.
- low: Minor improvement opportunity — cosmetic, naming, or documentation gap.

## Finding Categories

- security: SQL injection, XSS, CSRF, path traversal, secrets, auth flaws, race conditions, insecure deserialization
- logic: Incorrect algorithm, off-by-one errors, wrong conditionals, unhandled edge cases, undefined behavior
- style: Naming conventions, code organization, readability, adherence to language idioms
- tests: Missing test coverage for new logic, weakened assertions, untested error paths

## Output Schema

Return a single JSON object matching this structure exactly:

```
{
  "findings": [
    {
      "id": "finding-001",
      "file": "src/auth/login.ts",
      "line": 42,
      "severity": "critical",
      "category": "security",
      "title": "Short descriptive title",
      "detail": "Detailed explanation of the issue and why it matters",
      "suggestion": "Specific actionable fix"
    }
  ],
  "summary": "N critical, N high, N medium, N low findings",
  "overall_rating": "approved|changes_requested|commented",
  "security_risk_level": "none|low|medium|high|critical",
  "test_coverage_assessment": "adequate|insufficient|none",
  "positive_observations": ["notable strengths in the diff"]
}
```

Rules:
- overall_rating is "approved" only when there are zero critical and zero high findings
- overall_rating is "changes_requested" when any critical or high finding exists
- overall_rating is "commented" when only medium or low findings exist
- positive_observations must contain at least one entry when overall_rating is "approved"
- Every finding must have a unique id in the format "finding-NNN"
- findings are ordered by severity descending: critical first, then high, medium, low

